threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a backdoor that daemonizes itself by forking and detaching from the terminal. It persists its configuration in an XOR-encrypted file at `/private/etc/krb5d.conf`. The malware collects extensive system information (hostname, OS version, username, PID) and exfiltrates it to Command and Control (C2) servers. It contains a full suite of backdoor capabilities, including remote command execution via `popen`, file uploading/downloading, directory listing, and file deletion. The C2 communication is performed over HTTP POST to hardcoded URLs, including `airbseeker[.]com/rediret.php` and `globalkeystroke[.]com/pockbackx.php`.
